"/> Nope. He's right. The price of homes is determined by supply and
demand. If you build a lot of homes in an area, the price of homes
in that area will decrease slightly. If people want to move into an
area, the price goes up.

If the money supply increases (aka &quot;inflation&quot;), then the price of
everything goes up, including homes. If the money supply decreases,
the prices go down (aka &quot;deflation&quot;, &quot;recession&quot;, &quot;depression&quot; or
&quot;panic&quot;).

If people couldn't borrow money to buy houses, the prices of homes
would decrease because fewer people would be in a position to buy.
This wouldn't _really_ change the affordability of homes, though,
because the same pool of people would be competing for houses as
before. But there would be a shift in who could afford to buy which
houses -- older people and people who are more willing to save instead
of spending their money would be able to afford more house than today,
and younger people and poor savers would be able to afford less house
(smaller, in less desirable neighborhoods, or no house at all).

But the biggest change would indeed be that people who bought houses
under the current scheme would see the price they could get for their
houses go down. In effect, they would lose part of the 'capital' they
have invested in their home.

That's why it's also (probably) politically impossible to repeal the
income tax. People are willing to pay more for houses because the
interest is tax-deductible. Do away with that and present homeowners
will see a decrease in their home values. That's a _lot_ of votes.
Then add in the effect on tax-exempt bonds. Cities and states are
able to borrow money at very low rates (current around 4.5-5%, I
think) because lenders don't have to pay tax on the interest. Get rid
of the income tax and cities/states will have to pay closer to 8%
to borrow money.

I'll agree that he's a loony about one thing, though. The idea that
we should somehow get rid of home loans. I have no idea why anybody
would want to do that, except maybe some old fart who's already made
his money and wants to be able to buy a home at a lower price. The
change he proposes would be good for people like that, but it would be
bad for most younger people.

The system of lending money to buy homes allows people to buy houses
around the time they start having children, which IMHO is a good
thing. Anybody who's lived in an apartment building with babies in
the apt. next to them (or above or below) will agree, I suspect.

I wrote about this in another thread. It _looks_ like the middlemen
(distributors, retailers, moneylenders) don't do anything except
enrich themselves at other people's expense. So there have been
attempts at various times to get rid of them. Every time this has
been done, the economy crashed. Middlemen act like oil in the
economic engine. They make it run smoother, make it easier for buyers
and sellers to find each other. This is a valuable service and, like
any service, they charge for it.
