Just look what happened to housing prices over the last three years:
they shot up while the economy was in recession, and then in whats now
called a &quot;job-loss&quot; recovery. How could that happen? Interest rates
dropped, and each drop in interests rate allows you to borrow more for
the same monthly payment. When a rate drop allowed Joe Dokes to
borrow 250,000 where before he could only get $230,000 for the same
monthly payment he suddenly had no problem paying $20,000 more for the
same house, and, voila, the prices shot up.

You can see the same thing with cars and car loans. Fifteen years ago
car loans were for three years. For $500/mo for 36 mos at 8% you
could get at $15,000 loan. Then four and five year car loans became
standard. Longer loans mean you can borrow more money for the same
monthly payment. For $500/mo for 72 months at 8% (just to hold that
even) you can get a $25,000 loan. Sure enough, the average price of a
new car shot up. Of course all kinds of cool features that used to be
luxuries are now standard, so you can say we get more value for the
price increase, but the reality is that if people had been stuck with
3 year car loans the automakers would have kept power windows etc. as
options and not made them standard.

While I agree it seems like a good idea to let people borrow for home
mortgages, we have to acknowledge the dark side of long term
mortgages, which is the price inflation Eric is talking about.

